# RAG MCP Services — Setup and Usage

**User rule (global):** `%USERPROFILE%\.cursor\rules\mcp-rag-setup.mdc` — applies across all repos that use RAG documentation search.

> **Canonical source (Dedge):** `C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\.cursor\rules\mcp-rag-setup.mdc`

Centralized RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) indexes hosted on the app server via Python HTTP servers. These give Cursor and Ollama access to DB2, Visual COBOL, and Dedge source documentation without needing local copies.

## Available RAGs (FK environment)

| RAG | Port | Description |
|-----|------|-------------|
| `db2-docs` | 8484 | DB2 12.1 LUW manuals |
| `visual-cobol-docs` | 8485 | Visual COBOL 11 compiler messages |
| `Dedge-code` | 8486 | Dedge source code (COBOL, C#, PowerShell, Python, Node) and DB2 schemas |

> **FK registry endpoint (no auth):** `http://dedge-server:8484/rags`

## Cursor Setup (one-time)

Run the setup script from the DedgePsh repo:

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "<git-root>\DevTools\CodingTools\McpServers\Setup-RagMcpCursor\Setup-RagMcpCursor.ps1"
```

> **Canonical path (Dedge):** `C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\CodingTools\McpServers\Setup-RagMcpCursor\Setup-RagMcpCursor.ps1`

Or from deployed location:

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "$env:OptPath\DedgePshApps\Setup-RagMcpCursor\Setup-RagMcpCursor.ps1"
```

This auto-discovers RAGs from the AiDocNew API, creates a lightweight Python venv in `~/.cursor/rag-proxy/`, and updates `~/.cursor/mcp.json`. Restart Cursor after running.

### Verify

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "<git-root>\DevTools\CodingTools\McpServers\Setup-RagMcpCursor\Test-RagMcpCursor.ps1"
```

### Revert

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "<git-root>\DevTools\CodingTools\McpServers\Setup-RagMcpCursor\Setup-RagMcpCursor.ps1" -Revert
```

## Ollama Setup (one-time)

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "<git-root>\DevTools\CodingTools\McpServers\Setup-RagMcpOllama\Setup-RagMcpOllama.ps1"
```

> **Canonical path (Dedge):** `C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\CodingTools\McpServers\Setup-RagMcpOllama\Setup-RagMcpOllama.ps1`

Restart PowerShell, then use:

```powershell
Ask-Rag "What does SQL30082N reason code 36 mean?"
Ask-Rag "COBCH0779 error" -Rag visual-cobol-docs
Ask-Rag "Deploy-Files" -Rag Dedge-code
```

### Verify

```powershell
pwsh.exe -File "<git-root>\DevTools\CodingTools\McpServers\Setup-RagMcpOllama\Test-RagMcpOllama.ps1"
```

## Using RAGs in Cursor Chat

Each RAG appears as an MCP server with a `query_docs` tool. The agent calls them automatically based on the question topic:

- **DB2 questions** (SQL errors, security, configuration) → `db2-docs`
- **Visual COBOL questions** (compiler messages, language reference) → `visual-cobol-docs`
- **Dedge code questions** (where is a function, schema layout) → `Dedge-code`

Do not use `db2-docs` for COBOL questions or vice versa.

## How RAG Access Works

RAG services run as **Python HTTP servers directly** on the app server (ports 8484-8486). They are **unauthenticated** — no DedgeAuth, no JWT, no API keys. The Cursor MCP proxy and Ask-Rag function connect directly to these Python services over HTTP.

```
Developer Machine                          <app-server>
┌──────────────────┐                      ┌──────────────────┐
│ Cursor IDE       │                      │ Python HTTP RAGs  │
│  └─ MCP proxy ───┼── HTTP :8484-8486 ──►│  db2-docs         │
│     (stdio)      │                      │  visual-cobol-docs│
│                  │                      │  Dedge-code      │
│ PowerShell       │                      │                   │
│  └─ Ask-Rag ─────┼── HTTP :8484-8486 ──►│  (ChromaDB +      │
│     + Ollama     │                      │   ONNX embedding) │
└──────────────────┘                      └──────────────────┘
```

> **FK app server:** `dedge-server`

## Prerequisites

- Windows 11 / Windows Server 2025
- PowerShell 7+ (`pwsh.exe`)
- Python 3.11+ (Cursor setup only)
- Ollama installed from [ollama.com](https://ollama.com) (Ollama setup only)
- Network access to the app server hosting RAG services
